 and dormant companies</h2>\n\n<p>You must take additional steps:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>at the end of <a href=\"/first-company-accounts-and-return\" title=\"Your limited company's first annual accounts and Company Tax Return\">your company&rsquo;s first year</a></li>\n  <li>if you <a href=\"/restart-a-non-trading-or-dormant-company\" title=\"Restart a dormant company\">restart a dormant company</a></li>\n</ul>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/prepare-file-annual-accounts-for-limited-company/prepare-annual-accounts","slug":"prepare-annual-accounts","order":2,"title":"Prepare annual accounts","body":"<p>After the end of your company&rsquo;s financial year, you must prepare annual accounts - called &lsquo;statutory accounts&rsquo; - from the company&rsquo;s <a href=\"/running-a-limited-company/company-and-accounting-records\" title=\"Keeping records\">financial records</a>.</p>\n\n<p>You must always send copies of the statutory accounts to:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>all shareholders</li>\n  <li>people who can go to the company&rsquo;s general meetings</li>\n  <li>HM Revenue &amp; Customs (<abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>) as part of your Company Tax Return</li>\n  <li>Companies House (unless you send &lsquo;abbreviated&rsquo; accounts - see below)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>How to put together your company&rsquo;s statutory accounts</h2>\n\n<p>Statutory accounts must include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>a &lsquo;balance sheet&rsquo;, which shows the value of everything the company owns and is owed on the last day of the financial year</li>\n  <li>a &lsquo;profit and loss account&rsquo;, which shows the company&rsquo;s sales, running costs and the profit or loss it has made over the financial year</li>\n  <li>notes about the accounts</li>\n  <li>a director&rsquo;s report </li>\n  <li>an auditor&rsquo;s report</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A director must sign the balance sheet and their name must be printed on it.</p>\n\n<h3>Accounting standards</h3>\n\n<p>Your statutory accounts must meet either:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>International Financial Reporting Standards</li>\n  <li>UK Generally Accepted Accounting Practice</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.frc.org.uk/Our-Work/Codes-Standards/Accounting-and-Reporting-Policy/FRSSE.aspx\" title=\"Download 'Financial Reporting Standards for Small Enterprises' (PDF, 594KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Financial Reporting Standards for Small Enterprises’ (PDF, 594KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You can use accountants or tax advisers to make sure your accounts meet the standards.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Small companies, audit exemption and abbreviated accounts</h2>\n\n<p>Your company will be &lsquo;small&rsquo; if it meets 2 of the conditions below: </p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>its turnover is less than £6.5 million</li>\n  <li>it has less than £3.26 million on its balance sheet</li>\n  <li>it has fewer than 50 employees </li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If your company meets the legal requirements for &lsquo;small&rsquo; companies, you can:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>send shorter (&lsquo;abbreviated&rsquo;) accounts to Companies House created from the statutory accounts - this means less information about your company will be publicly available</li>\n  <li>use the exemption so your company&rsquo;s accounts <a href=\"/audit-exemptions-for-private-limited-companies\" title=\"Audit exemption for private limited companies\">don&rsquo;t need to be audited</a></li>\n  <li>choose not to file a copy of the director&rsquo;s report</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Abbreviated accounts</h3>\n\n<p>Abbreviated accounts are the balance sheet from the company&rsquo;s statutory accounts.</p>\n\n<p>The balance sheet must be signed by a director and their name must be printed on it.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You must still send full ‘statutory’ accounts to shareholders and to <abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> with your Company Tax Return.</p>\n</div>\n